<a href= "http://www.comixmatrix.com/members/profile.asp?id=192">My Comixmatrix Gallery</a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uacrisp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>acrisp</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/16/02 12:25:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=695.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Faye</span><hr size=1> Hmmmm... It's a fair idea, but there are a lot of gaps here that need to be filled.  I find the best SF stories I read (or watch) are set in well-thought-out universes.<br>
<br>
Your idea poses several questions:<br>
<br>
1. Why did these two teens decide not to live on Earth?<br>
<br>
2. What are the conditions on Earth?  And how far has humanity spread?  <br>
<br>
3. You say these kids don't have much money, and yet they can afford a vessel to travel to an abandoned space station - which I presume would not be on usual routes (think about it: when was the last time an airplane or a train stopped at a ghost town other than by accident?)  What does this say about the economy of this future era?  What does this say about the mode of interplanetary or interstellar travel?  <br>
<br>
4. Why was the station abandoned?  Who built it and for what purpose?  Is the station near any centers of civilization or is it in some remote and sparsely (if at all) settled region (this ties into the question of how far humanity has spread).<br>
<br>
5. What form of government and law exist in this future era?  Is there more than one government or sphere of influence?  <br>
<br>
6. Why are there people from Earth searching for these two teens?  <br>
<br>
I also recommend reading and watching a lot of SF to avoid cliches - this idea could concievably turn into a copy of several shows or books (such as Cowboy Bebop, Megatokyo, Lexx *shudder* or others) - and that is not a good thing.  When a story depends on cliches it demands more of the writer to make those cliches seem interesting, because most of the public will have seen those cliches time and again and are more likely to yawn at another rehash of an old idea than they are at a whole new idea.  <br>
<br>
Good luck!<br>
<br>
